    **THIS REVIEW CONTAINS MINOR SPOILERS**\
During moments of extreme heart pumping excitement we tend to lose all train of thought and rationality. We are blinded by the pure excitement of the moment and tend not to think twice about it. This of course can lead to a false sense of understanding in our judgement. Many adrenaline rush shows can bring on this affect and often lead to many offering immense praise because of it. But what happens when we take a step back and observe the bigger picture, when we as viewers see the forest from the trees. Our once immersive experience can become questionable to\
          \
        what's really presented before us.\
Today I'll attempt to do just that with Shingeki no Kyojin (Attack on Titan), a show that have garnered international success overnight and become a mainstay in casual conversation among many social groups.  A shounen  that plays out like a seinen in terms of execution, it is easy to see where the appeal for this anime lies. But that doesn't mean the mix is handled with proper finesse. We'll break apart this anime to see where it excels and what hindered it from being better.\
First we'll talk about the areas where this show shines: Animation & Sound\
Art/animation: 9/10\
If there was ever an area that many share similar sentiments about the show, it'll be in regards to its great use of cinematography. The 3D maneuver gear scenes easily draws parallels with the caliber demonstrated in blockbusters such as Spiderman's web-slinging city dive shots. This leads to a great cinematic experiences during these sequences that demonstrate great fluidity and attention to choreography. The show's aesthetics are also worthy of praise as it leads to actions that carry weight behind it, which is made more evident when fight sequences occur. The show also have a good grasp on capturing field of depth by allowing the foreground and background to make a clear distinction. Without such techniques the show can easily become a muddled mess, as demonstrated with people that fail to grasp that like Michael Bay. The love and effort placed into every action pact scene is very evident and one worthy of respect and admiration. Truly top tier status.\
Another notable accomplishment is the shows attention to detail concerning it's world building. Many shounens tend to skimp on this area, with their environment simply being treated as set piece for fights but AOT doesn't leave it at that. Instead it takes the time to properly flesh out it's settings and environment, which allows for easy immersion for the viewer. Drawing inspiration from mid-evil European architecture, this distinction helps establish a sense of identity for the title. Also the arstyle is unique for having heavily outlined characters, whether or not you like this depends on your individual tastes. The titan designs also differ, showing multiple variations. Although it may not seem like a big deal to many, it's certainly better than seeing hoards of look alikes that are mostly common with shows that have this kind of survival setting (Terra Formars cockroaches for example). The color pallet mostly consists of earthly tones with saturated greens and browns. This also helps enhance the medieval setting the show takes apart of.\
Sound: 8/10\
\"Heavy hitting\" is possibly the best way to quickly describe the soundtrack. With larger than life orchestric tracks accompanied with powerful ballads, it works hand in hand with AOT's energetic pace. This gives the show great synchronicity and helps enhance the given scenes on display.\
As far as voice acting goes it seems that everyone only have one tone however...LOUD... and with that it's hard to properly gauge any standouts. All accept Mikasa since being a robot doesn't compute with vocal rage.\
\
Now we'll shine a spotlight on the obvious problems that hinder the show: Story & Characters\
\
Story: 5/10\
The story is fairly standard fare in most post-apocalyptic setups but the setting is where it distinguishes itself.. Humanity is on the brink of extinction due to the attacks of giant humanoid creatures known simply as Titans. Because of their constant indiscriminate attack on humans the remaining members of society take shelter behind huge walls. Very little are known about the Titans which give them an ominous presence and leave us as viewers curious to their true motives. \
Where the problem lies is the direction of the story and how it is handled. The first couple of episodes showed no signs of slowing down and left you coming back for more. But then it went from being powered by Duracell to slowing down to turtle speed, this inconstant pacing really placed a damper on things. Of course since the show like to leave you on a cliffhanger every episode you'll find yourself powering through it anyways. The change of pace wouldn't be a problem if any sense of proper progression was shown, or even if it dedicated that time to fleshing out the cast. But unfortunately that never happens, instead what we get is a plot that aimlessly wonders around with no clear cut goal. But when there was an objective it took entirely too long to accomplish it. A bad example being a string of episodes dedicated to Eren placing a boulder in a breach in the wall. The show takes simplistic tasks like this and stretches it out to an unbearably long time. Sadly it does this frequently which just feels like useless padding to reach the desired runtime length. Also the show opts out to showing us lots of SHOCK FACTOR moments, which just comes off as a cheap gimmick to keep us from losing focus.\
Characters: 3/10\
Possibly the biggest blunder to address that both casual and critical thinkers alike can spot with this title lies with it's poorly handled cast. Needless to say this show has become infamous for its excessive fodder kills. For the sake of not addressing the nameless nobodies that end up dead I'll stick to talking about the 3 main characters.\
Never has a character been as bombastically pig headed as Eren since the likes of Kamille Bidan from Zeta Gundam. And for those who've had the displeasure of seeing Kamille's overblown angst in Zeta, you know that statement alone speaks VOLUMES about the kind of person we're dealing with. Although it should be noted that he gradually become more tolerable as the show goes on, he still remains 2 dimensional for the entire runtime. This is also made worse by the fact that he's plot armored to all hell. The \"kill em all\" kind of MC isn't bad though, as I'll take that over the overused \"self insert\" blank slates we seem to get by the dozen recently. \
Armin is the only decently characterized person in the show and follows the formulaic setup of the \"coward turned useful friend\". Although not original it is still welcomed when the rest of the cast remains 1 note archetypes. \
Mikasa, or the Hax Terminator if you prefer, is very one note. She is portrayed as a Mary Sue which in turn gives her the personality of a brick wall... until of course \"onii-can\" is in trouble and she goes full fledged yandere. They try to explain this away with her backstory but that doesn't change the fact that it feels very forced at times. This gives her a very inconsistent characteristic, making her the worse in the bunch in terms of proper characterization. Just think of her as the \"one woman army\" Titan killer and call it a day.\
Also expect yelling..lots and lots of yelling. If the script was written out EVERYTHING WOULD APPEAR IN ALL CAPS LIKE THIS... Depending on your tolerance for melodrama this can quickly becomes taxing and can also break immersion far too often. This becomes even more apparent if watch dubbed since you won't be occupied reading, instead watching everyone talk like they've never heard of an inside voice before. \
The government and nobles aren't treated with any tact and come across as 1 dimensional villains. The writers don't bother to flesh any of them out and make them evil just so we can hate them or to conjure up forced drama.\
If you over saturate a show with a certain event it ceases to hold any substance. And in regards to death with AOT that's exactly what happens. Outside of our plot armored main characters, all side characters are open season for Titan canon fodder. Sure the SHOCK FACTOR can keep you attentive but it also degrades the show's integrity. You start remembering the characters for how they died rather than who they were. They become apart of the blood splattered decorated background of the show and we are left giving no fucks. It feels rather juvenile and makes it hard to take the show seriously. It's hard to invest or care about a character if they die as quickly as they're introduced. Something AOT seem to fail to grasp.\
Enjoyment: 9/10\
All my qualms regarding the story and characters didn't negate my enjoyment of the show. It may have hindered me from taking it seriously but as a popcorn flick this title had me hooked. It gave me that rush I was looking for and the cinematography is some of the best I've seen in recent memory. It's an easily rewatchable show and a highly recommendable one as a gateway for new fans.\
Overall: 6/10\
If you simply seek intense action in a immersive setting look no further. This anime will easily scratch that itch. As entertainment value goes it's truly a roller coaster ride. However if you wanted a well written show you'd be hard pressed finding it here. Under the guise of it's nice setting lies a subpar script that I can't offer any praise too. With that in mind your enjoyment of this titles all depends on how you approach it as a viewer. \
\
For similar titles I recommend:\
\
Sidonia no Kishi: commonly referred to as \"attack on titan in space\" it has truly earned it's nickname. With giant monsters that pose a threat to society, and the remaining members fighting to survive. They are both also chalk filled with shock factor and have a high body count if that's something you seek.\
Shingeki no Bahamut: Genesis : Besides the similarities in name they both share hair raising action scenes, a fast pace when the time calls for it and a cool mid-evil setting. As a popcorn flick you will not be disappointed.\
Claymore: with a similar setting and humanity being attacked by monsters this makes of a decent substitute for fans of AOT. \
