    We have a weird obsession with our own self-destruction. Itâ€™s not just stories about how weâ€™re destroying the Earth. We are attracted to the sight of humans being butchered, cut up and eaten. The arts have constantly provided a safe place for people to view these things, knowing these people arenâ€™t really dying.\
As profound and deep as it sounds, it also gave rise to exploitation films. Sometimes, they get a budget and we get something like the Saw series. The worst offenders are those that use the grimâ€™nâ€™dark atmosphere of violence to shock. The audience for Saw is there for the visual spectacle, but many\
          \
        people are still sure grimdarkness is a sign of depth and maturity. Just look at all those crappy FPS games with monochromatic tough guys, or that very popular fantasy series thatâ€™s all about who will be the king.\
The premise sure sounds like it will join these ranks. Anime is full of overblown violence, especially in shows with a very serious tone. Thereâ€™s also a realistic art style to boot. After a few episodes, though, you notice you spent more time with the characters rather than looking at titans eating humans.\
Attack on Titan never feels like itâ€™s even trying to join the rank of shlock grimdarkness. This is a very humane story, one where the characters are much more important than what happens next. It doesnâ€™t even sink into exploitating their suffering. Itâ€™s far more excited with the variety of humans to linger on one detail.\
Calling Attack on Titan a story that loves humans sound silly. Heads are being chopped off and there are a lot of assholes around, but thatâ€™s the strength. It looks at humanityâ€™s worst aspects, admits their exist and still refuses to give up on it.\
In fact, itâ€™s a criticism of such misanthropy. The titans are distorted versions of us. Thatâ€™s a visualization of how misanthropes see humanity â€“ as senseless animals just bent on destruction. Yet the whole purpose the titans exist, just to chop humans to destroy them all is the logical end of misanthropy.\
Itâ€™s not a caricature, though. The creators understand why misanthropes exist in the first place. Cruelty is everywhere. Sometimes itâ€™s cliches about how the elite only cares about themselves (Thankfully, the series doesnâ€™t linger on that too much). Sometimes we get a more interesting look at how assholes are born. A military police officer canâ€™t hear the explanation of how all these destruction is going to get humanity anywhere. Right now his own world is under attack. We care more about our home environment than we do about humanity as a whole.\
Caring about the whole isnâ€™t easy. The series presents two ways of doing it. Either persevere as if nothing is happening and hide behind the walls, or make great sacrifices, risk losing everything but also gain everything.\
Itâ€™s not an easy choice at all. The ideal situation is that Erwinâ€™s plans will work, but thereâ€™s no guarantee it will. Weâ€™re always encouraged to take risks, but the reason itâ€™s a risk in the first place is because of the possibility of failure.\
Failure is an ever-looming presence in Attack on Titan. Plans never go as expected, and sometimes even Erwin isnâ€™t sure where to go from that failure. The series asks whether the risk is worth taking even if the plan fails. It doesnâ€™t present a simplistic, complete failure. The characters always gain something from the risks they take. A complete loss is easy to write and doesnâ€™t leave much to explore. Rather, it asks whether what was gained was worth the exchange.\
While this focus on dealing with failure is admirable (and possibly pretty rare in these types of anime), it sometimes become repetitive. The series never sinks into milking its tragedy. We see titans eating humans, but just enough to understand the horror of it all. The camera never lingers on dead bodies and titans chewing on a human. We still get an overpowered enemy for the ending, though.\
The last part of the series goes in a different direction. Itâ€™s a nice risk, but Iâ€™m still not sure whether it was worth it. Itâ€™s an extended action sequence thatâ€™s well-animated and exciting, but can feel too out-of-place. Up until then the series was concerned with the characters. We got various worldviews and personalities and saw them interact. The training arc is especially great. The action sequence relies on more on what will happen next than on the characersâ€™ personalities.\
