Too bad their enemy is pretty dull. It borders on invincible. Fighting an all-powerful enemy can be used well, but only psychologically (As in Harlan Ellisonâ€™s story about mouths and screaming). An action scene against an enemy who can block each attack quickly becomes repetitive. Thereâ€™s a reason why the last fighting scene in Medabots is so short.\
The enemy is given the occasional downfall and these are the most intense moments. Anytime it breaks out and finds a way around thereâ€™s a sense of been-there-done-that. At that point, it just felt like the creators was dragging the series on and piling on tragedies.\
Up until then, it constantly kept moving forward and didnâ€™t linger on unnecessary details. The reason we get these time skips because we donâ€™t need 40 episodes of Erenâ€™s childhood to understand him. Weâ€™re given enough to understand and then it moves on. Why linger on the least exciting section? Maybe theyâ€™re trying to appeal to an audience whoâ€™s in it for the action. At least they gave them unique action scenes.\
Overpowered enemy means the ending isnâ€™t very different than what happened a few episodes before it. The lack of conclusion isnâ€™t the big problem. The manga keeps going, and the series doesnâ€™t put all its money on the Big Conclusion anyway. The conclusion is not satisfying enough, but it doesnâ€™t negate all that came before. The problem is that not enough changed when it ends. Change is only hinted at, but the enemy hasnâ€™t been really defeated and not a lot of progress was made. I did not want all points wrapped up, but I wanted a lesson learned. A good ending is one that wraps up the themes, not plot points.\
The series also gets credit for changing my view on realistic character design. My previous experience was with Monster, where everyone looked like real people and no one looked interesting or unique. Animation gives total control. The animators decide everything â€“ the size of the head, the shape of the eyes, the color of the hair.\
There is supposed to be a good reason to include a detail. If not, itâ€™s just meaningless fluff with no purpose. Thatâ€™s why, in cartoons, the characters tend to have ridiculous designs that are either interesting to look at or to inform us about the characterâ€™s personality. Attack on Titan has this attention to detail. The facial expression especially have a lot of work put into them. Levi has small, narrow eyes that reflect his world thatâ€™s nothing but killing titans. Erenâ€™s eyes are wide but muscular, which fit with his idealism, extremist views and desire to go to the world outside. Petra also has such wide eyes, but theyâ€™re softer. Sheâ€™s more emphatic than anyone around here.\
