                          \
    Shingeki no Kyojin, or more commonly referred to as Attack on Titan, is a series that blew up in popularity almost instantly after its premiere, and there's little question as to why. Having a unique and compelling setting, brutal and realistic deaths, and absolutely amazing art and animation to bring the series to life, what is there not to like?\
My friend clued me in on this anime just as it was starting and I fell immediately in love with it. I marathoned it until the latest aired episode (episode 8 at the time) and wanting more I turned to the manga to sate my curiosity\
          \
        of what happens next. What's in the motherf@%king basement!? But, after picking up the manga I quickly realized this series was greatly flawed and all my excitement and drive for AoT was lost. I stopped paying attention to the series, despite all the uproar about it, and went on my way.\
A few days ago, however, I realized that the anime was surely finished by now, so I may as well give it another go to see if my latest impressions had changed at all. To my dismay, they didn't.\
This review will go over the strengths and weaknesses of AoT, going into detail the reasons why I feel so disappointed with how the series turned out. \
STORY - 4/10\
Much in the same way of Sword Art Online, AoT draws us in with its interesting and compelling setting. A new species of creature, the Titans, arose out of nowhere and have hunted humans to their final stand. Desperate for survival, the humans of this world have surrounded their race with towering walls that block them from the outside world and, more specifically, from the threat of the Titans. 100 years these walls have kept the humans safe and have established a time of peace, until a Colossal Titan appears and breaks through the outermost wall. Titans flood in through the new gap, and humanity is pushed back even further inside the cage they have constructed.\
The story of AoT is about humanity struggling to survive and fighting back against the threat of their impending extinction. The plot revolves around a group of people who are tasked with fighting against the titans and ensuring the survival of humanity. Sorry, let me rephrase that. That is what the story \"should\" have been, but unfortunately what we got fell short of this goal.\
Presentation is everything when it comes to a good story. No matter how fantastic and compelling your setting is if you can't tell it well then it's all wasted potential. And that's all I can see with AoT: wasted potential. The series starts out strong. Absurdly so. It sets up the scenario, it illustrates the titans as being a clear and devastating threat, it gets you seriously invested into what will happen next, and it even sets up a few mysteries for you to contemplate over in the background. And then, after a major event, the entire shift and focus of the series changes, arguably for the worst, and it hasn't yet recovered from that shift. I'll detail more about this in the \"Characters\" section of this review.\
ART AND ANIMATION - 10/10\
This is by far the anime's greatest strength and is no doubt largely the reason it has become so popular and widely acclaimed. It's likely this is the first thing you will notice about the anime from the very first minute you lay your eyes upon it. It's gorgeous. Stunning. Dazzling. Complete ecstasy for your eyes. There's no other way to put it. Characters are contrasted heavily with the environment, allowing for more detail to be put into both. Animation is some of the smoothest I have ever seen, boasting some of the most impressive and energetic action scenes I've ever experienced in an anime.Additionally, the quality of the art and animation stays fairly consistent throughout all 25 episodes. \
It's a perfectly reasonable thing to watch this show simply for the amazing art and animation. I can certainly say that I did, and I don't regret it one bit. It was this anime's saving grace for me.\
SOUND AND VOICE ACTING- 8/10\
The sound quality of AoT is overall outstanding. Where it really shines the most is during the action scenes, where there is a lot of face paced and epic scores used to get your adrenaline to flow. The screams and roars of rampaging titans are chilling, attacks and hits look and sound brutal, and the screams of the humans who constantly fall victim are done well.\
Voice acting is also really solid. The voice actor for Eren, Yuuki Kaji, really outdid himself during the moments when his character was fueled with rage and anger. Those are some of the most favorable moments for me in the series because of how well done they were.\
However, it's not perfect like art and animation is. There are some questionable scores used during some action scenes that don't seem to fit, and there are certain characters whose voice I really couldn't stand, such as the cowardly commander Kitts Verman.\
Overall, though, the sound design was much more a boon to the series than a fault.\
CHARACTERS - 3/10\
The characters of AoT are, without any doubt, the series greatest weakness. The 3 main characters are, in my opinion, unfit to be leading roles while the supporting cast is largely composed of bland and uninteresting personalities or are completely one dimensional in design. There's only a handful of characters worth their salt, but they either don't have enough screen time or are not significant enough to matter. Much of the wasted potential of this series comes from the main character, Eren, and what should have happened with him rather than what did. \
Instead of explaining who the characters are and their role in the story (you can easily just read their dedicated page on MAL), I want to talk about what they bring to the story, and why I'm so dissatisfied with them.\
> Armin \"Mr. Useless\" Arlert - This character is your typical smart-but-weak archetype who comes up with all the plans and tactics but is complete f@%k all in a fight. That in itself is fine, but for all he is supposed to be he accomplishes practically nothing in the series. Aside from having a single moment of glory, he is pretty much entirely irrelevant. Much of the realizations he has are either already known or are simultaneously figured out by someone more important than him, and in the end only really relays information that we've already found out.  My biggest complaint with this character, however, stems from his monologues of wanting to be strong and not having to be saved, and then not doing anything about that and having to be saved. Over and over and over.\
> Mikasa \"Mary-Sue\" Ackerman - While she is the most balanced out of all the main characters, this is largely the case because her only flaw is her complete lack of a personality. I mean that literally. It's her only flaw. She is downright amazing at everything she does, and is even stated to be worth 100 normal soldiers at one point. She can stand toe to toe with titans that just killed multiple \"elite\" soldiers effortlessly, despite being completely new to fighting titans (because lol). She is also obsessed with Eren. Or rather, she is obsessed with protecting him. Literally 80% of her dialogue stems from trying to dissuade Eren from doing reckless stuff or trying to protect/rescue him in some way. Aside from that one aspect, her personality is nonexistent.\
Eren \"The Plot\" Yeager - Yes, you read that right. Eren is the literal plot of AoT. I don't mean the plot revolves around him, or he is central to it. No, he IS the plot. And it's such a shame too, because it ruins his otherwise promising character. He starts off, just like the setting of AoT, very strong as a lead character. He's fun to watch, and you can relate to him because of the events that unfold. You feel for him. He's a good character because, while flawed, has a ton of passion and energy. He's hotheaded and quick to act out of rage and anger, and often makes stupid decisions as a result, leading Mikasa to having to try and dissuade him from doing something. But that's fine. He's a functional character.\
And then something big happens. (Slight spoilers for episode 5 and 8. Skip to next paragraph if you do not wish to be spoiled) What happens is what got me excited for AoT and compelled me to read through the manga. Eren sacrifices himself to save Armin, and ends up \"dying\" in the process. This is HUGE because this is the kind of event that shapes and molds the other main characters into respectable and powerful leads. Armin is traumatized and Mikasa shows actual emotion, which is awesome. There is a whole episode about remembering Eren and how he impacted Armin and Mikasa, and everything is pointing to how these 2 characters are going to develop and grow because of Eren's sacrifice... And then Eren comes back with a nifty new power up. Ugh.\
Now, that in itself is fine. But what isn't fine is what Eren becomes after this. No longer is Eren part of Humanity's struggle for survival. Form this point on, Eren is humanity's \"hope\". And everything and onward is about Eren. All other characters are reduced to insignificance in the presence of our leading protagonist. Everything that happens in the series revolves around Eren. Eren needs to do this! Eren needs to do that! OH NO! Eren couldn't do that! Quick, save him! (Spoiler, get used to that pattern, it'll be most of season 2)\
If you ignore what the series \"could\" have been, and, Eren still has some faults. Like stated above, Eren has a ton of passion in the beginning of the anime. And it's engaging. It keeps you interested in seeing how he's going to blow up. But near the end of the anime, you see almost none of this. No passion, no anger. He just frets over the deaths of his comrades over and over and gets really whiny when he makes a bad decision. Almost every time he fails at something, there needs to be at least 3-4 characters who yell at him for 5 minutes in order for him to do something again. Eren is just full of wasted potential, both for his character and for the plot, and it's likely that will never change.\
ENJOYMENT - 6/10\
Lackluster characters and missed opportunities aside, AoT is still a fun watch. It's somewhat like Gurren Lagann where you will enjoy it a lot more if you just turn off your brain and bask in the glorious visuals and epic battles. It does what it sets out to do, which is to entertain, and it does it well.\
Unfortunately, I'm not that kind of watcher, and a lot of the little things got to me throughout the experience. For example, a lot of characters in AoT have the tendency to jinx themselves right before a horrible event, especially Eren. Both Titan attacks were preceded with a monologue of how everything is going to be spiffy moments before the invasions, as well as many deaths happening to characters just after they, or someone else, explains how everything is going to be all right.\
Speaking of which, nearly all the deaths that happen in AoT happen to insignificant no-name no-face characters that are put there just to die. Only rarely do we ever see a character we know perish, and even then we barely know them. These characters, at best, have screentime for an episode or 2 before their death. There's no build up for them and thus no impact. Never once watching AoT did I ever fear for an established character's life (barring episode 5). However, I can respect that characters die quick and brutally, leaving no room for a dying speech that ever so populate anime these days.\
CONCLUSION - 6/10\
All in all, Attack on Titan is fun to watch for the amazing animation and the epic scenes, but not much more.\
My final score is:                     31/50 -> 6.2/10\
