    Years have passed since one of the most breathtaking moments in modern anime (that being, the sudden apparition of the Giant Titan) impacted both audiences and critics in equal measure; and despite the many subsequent \"mainstream\" hits that followed the very same footsteps, Shingeki no Kyojin still remains as the unarguably most talked-about anime of the present decade. And that's not without a reason: out of all popular on-going shÅnen manga prior 2013, Shingeki no Kyojin was undoubtedly the most intriguing. \
Set in a post-apocalyptic future, when giant humanoid creatures referred as Titans have already devoured most of the human population, the story revolves around\
          \
        a young boy, Eren, and all the chaos unleashed by Titans after destroying the wall protecting the last human stand in the world. Such a fascinating premise could have easily been brought down by mediocre decisions from part of the studio responsible of the animated adaptation. Yet despite many weaknesses the show carries along, the final product is a satisfying chiller full of twists-&-turns, clever cliffhangers and solid development of its main characters.\
To begin with, the series presents one of the most enthralling first episodes ever conceived, from our main characters brief background description to the absolutely amazing gorefest that comes afterwards. The plot, once in full motion, never ceases to thrill, with one twist after another, even if some of them might come a bit too repetitive. As a whole, the first mid-cour does enough on its own to stand as one of the most entertaining and effectively suspenseful series out there, which is no surprise when you have Tetsurou Araki to direct this beast of an adaptation.\
But as much as one can praise the first half of the show, it's undeniable the escalating decline in quality during the second half. For many reasons, most characters that once resulted highly entertaining to watch lose both screentime and appeal. Plus, the fact that the plot begins to show many contrivances and pretty deplorable \"mysteries\" by this time just makes it worse. And knowing how the source material was far from getting things wrapped up any soon, it's pretty obvious that the conclusion would just leave audiences disappointed.\
The characters, while not exactly complex or developed to the bone, have their fair share of characterization.The cast is composed by Eren, a young boy who seeks revenge for her mother's death by hands of a Titan; Mikasa, his over-protective sister; and Armin, the loyal childhood friend. Several other characters get introduced with time, and while most of them are relatively interesting, I just can't avoid thinking of them as mere archetypes with interesting motivations and quirky traits; with the exception of Sasha (the eccentric potato-eater of the group) and Armin, who manage to be highly memorable and likable all-around.\
The production values, though, are something of their own league. The drawing style is distinctively bold with emphasis in facial expressions, giving it an essentially comic-like vibe. The animation is fluid and detailed. The soundtrack is majestic and epic. The opening and closing themes are both invigorating and mesmerizing. You name it: there's simply no technical aspect where Shingeki no Kyojin fails at surpassing expectations.\
After all, high-concepts are meant to give lots of entertainment and leave audiences in awe. And in those two standalone camps, Shingeki no Kyojin does far more than enough.   \
