    Attack on Titan is one of the most overhyped anime ever thatâ€™s biggest complaint, for me, is that people canâ€™t shut the hell up about it. Anywhere you go thatâ€™s even vaguely anime related youâ€™re bound to find something going on related to Attack on Titan because itâ€™s an easily accessible show that many people will feel edgy for watching; when, in the end, theyâ€™re watching a shounen with some splotches of blood and rampant murder to make you feel like youâ€™re watching something more adult.\
The plot of Attack on Titan is very basic for a fantasy. Big, lumbering giants are attacking the fortified walls\
          \
        of the last bastion of humanity. Branches of military battle Paul Bunyan in an attempt to exterminate them before they exterminate humanity. When they break through one of the walls and kill countless people, Eren Jaegar, our hero, watches his mother get eaten and decides along with his adopted sister to join up with the military and fight the bastards who took away his life.\
Why is this basic, you ask? Because as far as fantasy goes this is a very unrealized world. Itâ€™s essentially one city and a bunch of monsters. It works because of its simplicity and pulls people in because itâ€™s easy enough for everyone to understand. Wall, bad monsters, good military, fighting!\
Thatâ€™s not to say the plot is particularly bad in anyway. Itâ€™s just very slow moving and shounen-esque. The series starts off rather strongly and goes at a decent clip but the further you go in, the more plodding it gets. Ten minute action sequences get drawn out to ridiculous lengths because of brooding characters and constant flashbacks to things that donâ€™t matter. Episode twenty-threeâ€™s ending sets up an awesome fight that gets you pumped up. But then episode twenty-four comes on and spends half the episode brooding and flashing back to more brooding. I understand the characters are all depressed and have all seen things but I donâ€™t want to sit through their constant coming to terms with the fact that things are fucked up.\
Thatâ€™s how the action sequences mostly go. So much time is spent talking about what they will do or brooding over all the things that have happened that any excitement to be had is lost and the scenes fall flat. Watching a bunch of sword wielding Spider-Men swing around a giant nude anatomy lab model should be exciting and fun. But most of the time, thereâ€™s too much going on on the sidelines and this is where you can see that this is truly a shounen.\
Another major problem I had with the plot was how needlessly dark and depressing it is. Okay guys, I understand that people die in war. I also understand that titans kill a lot of people. But I donâ€™t need to see every death onscreen. It doesnâ€™t add anything. Watching hundreds of faceless people die gives the show a feeling of childish masochism and ruins any emotion the audience can get from a main character dying. â€œHow do we make this hardcore? Like, so hardcore people will think theyâ€™re watching something more than an above average shounen?â€\
